Here is a C++ program to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) 
        return n;
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2); 
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;

    cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is " << fib(n);
    return 0;
}
```

This program takes the nth term to find as input from the user. The fib() function implements the recursion. Base cases are fib(0) = 0 and fib(1) = 1. For any other nth term, fib(n) = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2). This recursive formula keeps calling itself until one of the base cases is reached.

The time complexity of this naive recursive solution is exponential O(2^n) as there are many redundant subproblem calculations. It can be improved to linear time complexity using dynamic programming and memoization.

